snippet.textDisplay: That's the problem when pigs go camping. It has been like this for years. They know that nobody will catch them. I used to go camping in the Victorian district of Ensay back in the 70's, pristine spots that nobody knew and we always left it as it was by taking our rubbish home. But then, in the coming years, the population explosion of disrespectful people in the 80's gold rush made them spread into such places in the quest for gold, and when we returned to the same places we loved during the gold rush we found the camping spots and areas littered with stuff the same as the crap seen in this video. It got worse in the 90's with new litterbugs who spoiled the campsites with their rubbish that we stopped what we had loved the most, camping. Nowadays those who go camping or shooting deer are the worst offenders. When we went to places that had other campers there, when they left at the end of the weekend they left the rubbish behind, even their campfires were left intact, still burning. These people don't deserve the bush, camping, hiking, etc., they are selfish, arrogant, disrespectful and mean. We had sometimes argued with them about taking the rubbish home prior to departing and they looked at us as if to say mind your business. What are they going camping for then? Back in our days, we always had an occasional Ranger patrolling the campsites or wherever there was campfire smoke and we were proud that those guys were around, proud enough to offer a coffee and chat. Not anymore, since the Government had shut down the Forestry services of which I wanted to be a Ranger too, back in the early 70's. It's a good thing that you guys are cleaning these spots but I hope you would also catch the ignorant, poorly educated, low IQ, thinkless sons of bitches that have an attitude like Louie the Fly, messing and littering camping grounds in our forests.

snippet.textDisplay:
Recently, whilst travelling oversees, walking in a National Park, I saw something similar and said to the locals there, "I've never seen anything like this in Australia". Obviously, I'm naive. I would never have imagined this ever happening in remote areas in Australia in a bazillion years!
Mind you, I am talking like 1960's - 2000. I never once ever saw plastic bottles, wrappers, butts, nothing, anywhere I ever hiked. So the only conclusion I can come up with is that it's rich, entitled tourists from overseas who think that it's someone else's job to pick things up. It's only been in the past 15-20 or so years that many of these places have been more easily accessible to overseas tourists (since the advent of the World Wide Web).
I really hope that in the next decade or so that DNA testing will become much improved to the point that they'll be able to scan an empty coke can and look it up in a database and then put those grubby maggots in jail. It's the only way to teach these mongrels.

snippet.textDisplay:
I never made it up to the Cape whilst I was in Australia but I seen that exact thing in a lot of different places. Once on Fraser Island in Central Station Camp Site which as you'll know has a refuse point we ran after a 2 car group (I'll refrain from naming the nationality) and forced them into taking their rubbish they'd left strewn all across their spot, apparently beer cans become useless when you empty them... They took it with them all the couple of hundred yards to the refuse point but only after quite a heated argument.

Unfortunately we have the same here in Scotland, we are lucky to have a right to roam act allowing us access through lands to wild camp, not so much 4wd but certainly hiking and being in the outdoors but that's all at risk at the moment with increasing tourism seeing people just discard what they want where they want and making trails or camp spots like what you just cleaned up.

Good effort cleaning up after the dogs.

Have had the same out at Morwell River in Gippsland near Morwell river falls, many camp spots and yeah they leave the rubbish, WHY they don't take it with them ?? No common sense.
Once discovered a whole trailer load dumped directly into the river, they had backed a 4WD tray back down and emptied it. Cleaned up and dragged out what we could, called the local EPA they came and cleaned up the remainder. Had the name address and phone number among the rubbish to id the people, but they were never prosecuted. The authorities need to dish out much harder penalties and legally pursue these people, we take vehicles and boats etc.. with illegal fishing and fire wood collection why not do the same for those who dump and litter.

snippet.textDisplay:
A few years back I took my 60 year old Mum out to the Macquarie Marshes in NSW. When we jumped out at a spot in the middle of the marshes there was crap absolutely f*g everywhere. She started picking up the rubbish and bagging it. I made a comment about it and she replied "Well, who else is bloody gonna clean it up?". After that remark, me, her, ol man and a mate spent about half an hour bagging up rubbish around the marshes and took it back into town.
That attitude has really stuck with me since. We always see things as "oh that's the government's responsibility" or "that's not my problem". Sometimes you just gotta take the responsibility onto yourself.

Later on the same trip we pulled into the Paroo river at Wanaaring. On the way down to the river, passed a bunch of 4wd utes heading out, all new vehicles, kitted for touring, clean looking folks all maybe in their 40's, not yobs, they all waved as we passed them in. Got down to the river and it was f*d. Freshly broken beer bottles everywhere, bags of rubbish floating in the billabong that appeared to have just been thrown in that morning. There was a lot of older rubbish as well but it was pretty clear those neat and tidy folks with friendly faces had been absolute pigs while they were camped there. I ended up cutting my hand on broken glass while having a swim in the river.

snippet.textDisplay: Reflect on this for a moment people....How many of us use the publication 'Camps' for recon work. Reflect back on how many great places have been removed (shut down) in this publication because of people being totally irresponsible to the campsite, the owners of the land, and there fellow travellers. As highlighted by Adv 4, it's going to get locked up,  but it should be you, you grubby bastards that trash the place. Wake up, keep Australia beautiful for all of us, especially the next generation. We all have camera's, take a few pic's especially if you are there witnessing the event. The internet is a powerful tool....I'm sure there number plate would look real good in highlighting this ever increasing problem.
